org.jcvi.jillion.internal.core.util.iter

Class PrimitiveArrayIterators

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jcvi.jillion.internal.core.util.iter.PrimitiveArrayIterators

  • public final class PrimitiveArrayIterators
extends Object
    PrimitiveArrayIterators provides factory methods to create Iterator of boxed primitives that iterate over primitive arrays. the Boxing is performed one element at a time and only when Iterator.next() is called.

    None of the returned iterators are thread-safe.

    Author:
    dkatzel

    • Method Detail

      • create

        public static Iterator<Integer> create(int[] array)
        Create a new Iterator that will iterate over all the elements of the given array. The iterator does NOT copy the array so any changes to the array while iterating will be reflected in the array.
        Parameters:
        array - the array of primitives to iterate over; can not be null.
        Returns:
        a new Iterator will never be null.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if array is null.

      • create

        public static Iterator<Integer> create(int[] array,
                                       int length)
        Create a new Iterator that will iterate over length elements of the given array starting at the offset 0.
        Parameters:
        array - the array of primitives to iterate over; can not be null.
        length - the number of elements to iterate over; must be <= array.length and >=0.
        Returns:
        a new Iterator will never be null.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if array is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if length < 0. or if the length is longer than the given array.

      • validateParameters

        public static void validateParameters(int length,
                                      int arrayLength)

      • create

        public static Iterator<Integer> create(int[] array,
                                       int start,
                                       int end)
        Create a new Iterator that will start at the specified start offset (inclusive) and end at the specified end offset (also inclusive).
        Parameters:
        array - the array of primitives to iterate over; can not be null.
        start - the start offset (inclusive) to begin iterating, must be a valid offset into the array.
        end - the end offset (inclusive) to stop iterating, must be a valid offset into the array.
        Returns:
        a new Iterator will never be null.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if array is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if start is greater than the end.
        ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException - if either start or end are out of bounds of the array.
